IAM Custom Policy


What is an IAM Custom Policy?

An IAM Custom Policy is a policy that you create to give specific permissions to IAM Users, Groups, or Roles.

Simple Definition

A Custom Policy allows you to define exactly what actions a user can or cannot perform in AWS.



Why Do We Use Custom Policies?

AWS provides many managed policies, but sometimes they give more permissions than required.

A Custom Policy allows you to give only the required permissions (Principle of Least Privilege).



Real-Life Example

Imagine an office.

Employee A should only view files.
Employee B should view and edit files.
Employee C should delete files.

Instead of giving everyone full access, you create different permission rules.

👉 This is exactly what a Custom Policy does.



IAM Policy Structure

A policy is written in JSON format.

Basic structure:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": "s3:ListBucket",
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}



Important Elements:

1. Version

Specifies the policy language version.

"Version": "2012-10-17"

Use this version for all new IAM policies.

2. Statement

Contains one or more permission rules.

"Statement": [ ]

3. Effect

Defines whether the action is:

Allow
Deny

Example:

"Effect": "Allow"

4. Action

Specifies what the user can do.




Examples:

s3:GetObject
s3:PutObject
ec2:StartInstances
ec2:StopInstances
ec2:DescribeInstances
5. Resource

Specifies which AWS resource the policy applies to.

Example:

"Resource": "*"

or

"Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::my-bucket/*"
Example 1 - Read Only S3 Access
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}


User can:

View buckets
Download files

User cannot:

Upload files
Delete files



Example 2 - Start and Stop EC2
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "ec2:StartInstances",
        "ec2:StopInstances"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}



The user can:

Start EC2
Stop EC2



The user cannot:
Terminate EC2
Create EC2
Advantages of Custom Policies
More secure
Gives only required permissions
Follows the Principle of Least Privilege
Reduces accidental changes
Managed Policy vs Custom Policy
Managed Policy	Custom Policy
Created by AWS	Created by You
General permissions	Specific permissions
Easy to use	More secure & flexible




Interview Questions
1. What is an IAM Custom Policy?

An IAM Custom Policy is a JSON document created by the user to define specific permissions for IAM users, groups, or roles.

2. Why do we use Custom Policies?

To provide only the required permissions, improving security by following the Principle of Least Privilege.

3. What are the main elements of an IAM Policy?
Version --> Statement --> Effect -->Action --> Resource


4. What is the difference between Allow and Deny?
Allow → Grants permission.
Deny → Explicitly blocks permission (takes precedence over Allow).
Easy Memory Trick

Think of an IAM policy as a permission slip.

Version → Policy format
Statement → Rules
Effect → Allow or Deny
Action → What can be done
Resource → On which AWS resource


